ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A genetic abnormality that arises from duplications of the juxtamembrane portion of the gene and results in constitutive activation of the FLT3 receptor tyrosine kinase protein in early hematopoietic progenitor cells. It is associated with acute myelogenous leukemia where it appears to correlate with a poor prognosis.

It is associated with acute myelogenous leukemia where it appears to correlate with a poor prognosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A mutation in the region of the FLT3 gene that encodes the second tyrosine kinase domain of the receptor-type tyrosine-protein kinase FLT3 that causes the stabilization of the activation loop of the kinase domain. FLT3 activation loop mutations lead to constitutive tyrosine kinase activity and are associated with acute myeloid leukemia.

Concepts.definition: A mutation in the region of the FLT3 gene that encodes the second tyrosine kinase domain of the receptor-type tyrosine-protein kinase FLT3 that causes the stabilization of the activation loop of the kinase domain. FLT3 activation loop mutations lead to constitutive tyrosine kinase activity and are associated with acute myeloid leukemia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene may play a role in endosomal vesicle fusion, extra-osseous calcification and inflammatory responses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An autosomal dominant hereditary neoplastic syndrome caused by an alteration in the p53 tumor suppressor gene.  It is characterized by the development of malignant neoplasms at various anatomic sites.  The malignant neoplasms associated with Li-Fraumeni syndrome include adrenal cortex carcinoma, astrocytic tumors, colorectal carcinoma, gastric carcinoma, malignant breast neoplasms, medulloblastoma, osteosarcoma, and soft tissue sarcomas.

Concepts.definition: An autosomal dominant cancer predisposition syndrome caused by germline mutations of the TP53 gene. It is associated with breast carcinoma, choroid plexus carcinoma, adrenal cortex carcinoma, astrocytic tumors, medulloblastoma, soft tissue sarcoma, osteosarcoma, and leukemia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene is involved in both DNA binding and transcriptional regulation.

Concepts.definition: This gene is involved in both DNA binding and transcriptional regulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene may play a role in RNA splicing and tumor suppression.

Concepts.definition: This gene may play a role in RNA splicing and tumor suppression.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene plays a regulatory role in transcription and in matrix metalloproteinase activity.

Concepts.definition: This gene plays a regulatory role in transcription and in matrix metalloproteinase activity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene plays a role in signal transduction and cytoskeletal remodeling.

Concepts.definition: This gene plays a role in signal transduction and cytoskeletal remodeling.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: This gene may be involved in endocytosis and the attenuation of receptor signaling.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation t(15;17)(q22;q21) which fuses the first 3 exons of the PML gene with the last 7 exons of the RARA gene. This fusion is associated with acute promyelocytic leukemia. Three transcript variants are possible based on the three breakpoint clusters in the PML gene.

Concepts.definition: A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation t(15;17)(q22;q21) which fuses the first 3 exons of the PML gene with the last 7 exons of the RARA gene. This fusion is associated with acute promyelocytic leukemia. Three transcript variants are possible based on the three breakpoint clusters in the PML gene.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fusion protein encoded by the BCR/ABL1 fusion gene. This protein is comprised of the N-terminus of the breakpoint cluster region protein fused to almost the entire tyrosine-protein kinase ABL1 protein.

Concepts.definition: A fusion protein encoded by the BCR/ABL1 fusion gene. This protein is comprised of the N-terminus of the breakpoint cluster region protein fused to almost the entire tyrosine-protein kinase ABL1 protein.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation t(16;21)(p11;q22) which fuses the FUS gene with the ERG gene. This rearrangement is associated with acute myeloid leukemia.

Concepts.definition: A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation t(16;21)(p11;q22) which fuses the FUS gene with the ERG gene. This rearrangement is associated with acute myeloid leukemia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cytogenetic aneuploidy abnormality that refers to the presence of one chromosome 5 only. It is associated with the development of refractory anemia with excess blasts, refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia, and refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia and ringed sideroblasts._A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 5 (5q). It is associated with the development of myelodysplastic syndrome with isolated deletion (5q), acute myeloid leukemia with multilineage dysplasia, and acute myeloid leukemia with myelodysplasia-related changes.

Concepts.definition: A cytogenetic aneuploidy abnormality that refers to the presence of one chromosome 5 only. It is associated with the development of refractory anemia with excess blasts, refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia, and refractory anemia with multilineage dysplasia and ringed sideroblasts.

A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 5 (5q). It is associated with the development of myelodysplastic syndrome with isolated deletion (5q), acute myeloid leukemia with multilineage dysplasia, and acute myeloid leukemia with myelodysplasia-related changes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A molecular abnormality indicating rearrangement of the MLLT10 gene.

Concepts.definition: A molecular abnormality indicating rearrangement of the MLLT10 gene.
